112
00:06:23,771 --> 00:06:27,012
So Wayward Strand is, as I said, our debut title.

113
00:06:27,192 --> 00:06:30,173
It's a narrative game set in regional Australia in 1978.

114
00:06:31,333 --> 00:06:34,814
And you play, as you saw, as Casey, who's a 14-year-old girl

115
00:06:34,894 --> 00:06:37,735
whose mother is the head nurse of a hospital,

116
00:06:38,015 --> 00:06:41,056
which just happens to be on an airship that's suspended in the clouds

117
00:06:41,156 --> 00:06:42,957
above your small regional town.

118
00:06:43,577 --> 00:06:46,097
It's the summer holidays, and your mum can't find anyone

119
00:06:46,117 --> 00:06:47,458
to look after you for a couple of days,

120
00:06:47,538 --> 00:06:49,258
so you go with her up to the hospital.

121
00:06:49,758 --> 00:06:53,499
And she gives you the job of spending time with the patients in the aged care ward, keeping

122
00:06:53,539 --> 00:06:56,440
them company and helping them out with anything that they need.

123
00:06:56,880 --> 00:06:59,181
So that's the setup for our real-time narrative game.

124
00:06:59,421 --> 00:07:03,722
Three days as a teenager, talking to the residents of this floating hospital, getting to know

125
00:07:03,782 --> 00:07:05,642
them, getting a brief glimpse into their lives.

126
00:07:06,203 --> 00:07:11,704
The game's about a four-hour round trip and is fully voiced by a cast of 15 superb actors.

127
00:07:13,192 --> 00:07:16,934
Many people contributed to the making of this game and we always like to highlight this.

128
00:07:17,234 --> 00:07:20,295
We find that the best ideas are found in the space between us.

129
00:07:21,056 --> 00:07:25,398
And as you'll hear throughout the talk, Jason and I are definitely not the authors of this game,

130
00:07:25,458 --> 00:07:27,879
especially not when it comes to the details of the stories.

131
00:07:28,359 --> 00:07:30,340
We're just the people who happen to write it down.

132
00:07:31,641 --> 00:07:34,002
Of the 33 fine people you saw on the slide before,

133
00:07:34,062 --> 00:07:36,243
the ones on screen now formed the core team.

134
00:07:36,323 --> 00:07:39,865
So these are the people who were along for long sections of the development journey

135
00:07:40,285 --> 00:07:42,766
or who directed significant parts of its development.

136
00:07:43,904 --> 00:07:48,227
As you may have noticed on the other slide, our team does come from outside of games.

137
00:07:48,448 --> 00:07:53,812
That's both in terms of who we are as non-binary people, women, people of color, neurodiverse

138
00:07:53,852 --> 00:07:58,235
people, new parents, people from working class backgrounds, and it's also in terms of our

139
00:07:58,255 --> 00:07:59,176
professional backgrounds.

140
00:07:59,316 --> 00:08:04,300
Some of us have come to video games from theater, or music, or comics, or VTubing.

141
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:06,201
And what this means is that...

142
00:08:06,962 --> 00:08:13,746
Although we all love to play video games, we know that video games are not made by us, about us, or for us all that often.

143
00:08:14,306 --> 00:08:17,168
When people like us appear in games, it's often as NPCs.

144
00:08:17,696 --> 00:08:22,619
With a few repeating lines of dialogue, a quest to give, and maybe a crush on the player character.

145
00:08:23,240 --> 00:08:27,082
And this has a deep and conscious impact on the kinds of games that we feel compelled to make.

146
00:08:27,682 --> 00:08:33,546
Wayward Strand is a game that strips back player agency and gives space and power to the NPCs.

147
00:08:33,826 --> 00:08:38,409
The gameplay is geared towards listening and caring for them, rather than enacting your own

148
00:08:38,429 --> 00:08:43,432
desires upon them. And this is deeply informed by who we are as a team and our lived experience.

149
00:08:44,533 --> 00:08:45,133
So that's the team.

150
00:08:45,714 --> 00:08:47,637
