156
00:09:03,247 --> 00:09:04,068
dabbled in writing.

157
00:09:04,948 --> 00:09:08,869
I come from a lot of writing experience, particularly in the theater, but had not even really dabbled

158
00:09:08,889 --> 00:09:09,709
in video games.

159
00:09:09,809 --> 00:09:16,030
I mean, I played Portal 2 on my MacBook with my trackpad, but nothing that could be considered

160
00:09:16,470 --> 00:09:17,750
actually making a digital game.

161
00:09:18,851 --> 00:09:22,691
Jason and I found very quickly, though, that we were a really good team.

162
00:09:23,231 --> 00:09:26,472
The disparity of our professional backgrounds meant that we brought different strengths

163
00:09:26,532 --> 00:09:26,992
to the team.

164
00:09:27,793 --> 00:09:32,256
But we're also really deeply curious about each other's work, so we were able and open

165
00:09:32,296 --> 00:09:34,237
to learn from each other throughout the process.

166
00:09:35,318 --> 00:09:39,141
It's also worth saying that Russell, who was on that slide, who mainly worked on programming

167
00:09:39,161 --> 00:09:42,203
throughout the game, was deeply involved in the ideation of the game.

168
00:09:42,283 --> 00:09:46,906
So a lot of the character ideas and broad brush strokes, plots, come from him as well

169
00:09:46,946 --> 00:09:47,527
as from Jason.

170
00:09:50,655 --> 00:09:56,476
So our initial inspirations for Wayward Strand came from our personal relationships with

171
00:09:56,536 --> 00:10:01,597
older people in our lives, stories that they've told or experiences that we shared with them.

172
00:10:03,117 --> 00:10:07,318
And we thought that older people's lives were really interesting to explore and have players

173
00:10:07,338 --> 00:10:12,419
think about, and to have represented within media, like outside of the cookie cutaway

174
00:10:12,479 --> 00:10:17,079
that a lot of old people are represented as mentors or sources of knowledge.

175
00:10:18,571 --> 00:10:20,652
Yeah, people that give you a sword or whatever.

176
00:10:21,293 --> 00:10:24,695
Instead, we wanted to present them with full lives

177
00:10:25,556 --> 00:10:26,477
in the present moment.

178
00:10:29,499 --> 00:10:31,260
Yeah, so Wayward Strand takes place

179
00:10:31,520 --> 00:10:33,262
across three in-game days,

180
00:10:34,042 --> 00:10:36,904
and all characters more or less live out those three days

181
00:10:37,064 --> 00:10:38,285
within view of the player.

182
00:10:39,586 --> 00:10:40,927
This allowed us to tell stories

183
00:10:40,987 --> 00:10:43,169
where the rhythms of daily life

184
00:10:43,269 --> 00:10:44,950
are a critical element of the stories.

185
00:10:46,134 --> 00:10:51,218
Unlike other media where a character has to have a cinematic moment of realization or

186
00:10:51,258 --> 00:10:56,482
a moment of conflict that drives the story forward, we could represent how stories and

187
00:10:56,522 --> 00:10:59,104
events take place more in real life.

188
00:10:59,404 --> 00:11:05,009
So messily, fits and starts, woven amongst other things that are happening in your life

189
00:11:05,629 --> 00:11:10,954
with important things sometimes taking place outside of the exciting cinematic moments.

190
00:11:12,841 --> 00:11:15,602
Like a kind of funny example of this is for a long time,

191
00:11:15,622 --> 00:11:18,302
we were aiming to get like toilets into the game

192
00:11:18,562 --> 00:11:21,443
and have each of the characters schedules,

193
00:11:22,203 --> 00:11:25,304
like bathroom schedule, interact with each of their stories.

194
00:11:26,324 --> 00:11:28,664
So maybe a character misses hearing a critical thing

195
00:11:28,704 --> 00:11:29,965
because they went to the toilet

196
00:11:30,025 --> 00:11:31,825
or maybe somebody excuses yourself

197
00:11:32,045 --> 00:11:33,245
when you're spending time with them

198
00:11:33,325 --> 00:11:34,606
just because nature called.

199
00:11:36,346 --> 00:11:37,186
But they could do that

200
00:11:37,266 --> 00:11:39,287
without any big narrative consequence sometimes.

201
00:11:39,307 --> 00:11:42,067
So it's a way to.

202
00:11:42,828 --> 00:11:48,434
bring in the feel of like reality that's quite unique to this real time storytelling format.

203
00:11:49,775 --> 00:11:53,339
Because if somebody is on the toilet in a movie, that's because maybe it's a comedy

204
00:11:53,459 --> 00:11:56,062
or maybe they're about to be strangled by James Bond.

205
00:11:56,583 --> 00:11:58,445
Shout out to objectively the best Bond movie, GoldenEye.

206
00:11:58,465 --> 00:11:58,785
But yeah, exactly.

