00:12:29,774 --> 00:12:37,482
a creator in a deliberate way as opposed to in this kind of semi-dynamic way that we have

225
00:12:37,542 --> 00:12:40,365
where if that happened, it would just happen within the game.

226
00:12:40,425 --> 00:12:42,448
It's not necessarily part of our plan.

227
00:12:46,365 --> 00:12:50,006
So I'll talk a little now about our process of consultation for fleshing out our characters.

228
00:12:50,506 --> 00:12:53,747
Our game has characters with a really broad range of lived experience.

229
00:12:54,007 --> 00:12:58,409
So we have many aged characters, of course, many of whom are experiencing chronic illness,

230
00:12:58,989 --> 00:13:03,050
as well as queer characters, a First Nations character, healthcare workers.

231
00:13:03,530 --> 00:13:07,071
And given that the point of our game, as we've been mentioning, was to show the richness

232
00:13:07,111 --> 00:13:11,312
of these characters' lives, it was important to us that we engage in consultation right

233
00:13:11,332 --> 00:13:15,413
from the start, and that we honored these relationships through to the end of our development

234
00:13:15,453 --> 00:13:15,693
journey.

235
00:13:16,906 --> 00:13:20,670
One of the first teams that we started working with on consultation was the Bonorong Land Council.

236
00:13:20,830 --> 00:13:25,855
And I'm going to focus on this consultation as a bit of a case study for how we engage in consultation.

237
00:13:26,515 --> 00:13:31,841
This was a really special relationship that we maintained throughout the entire lifecycle of the development of the game.

